===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr|en}} {{m|fr|apologie}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{m|la|apologia}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|ἀπολογία||a speech in defence}}, from {{m|grc|ἀπολογοῦμαι||I speak in one's defense}}, from {{m|grc|ἀπόλογος||an account, story}}, from {{m|grc|ἀπό||from, off}} (see ''[[apo-]]'') + {{m|grc|λόγος||speech}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/əˈpɒl.ə.dʒi/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-apology.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|apologies}}

# An expression of [[remorse]] or [[regret]] for having said or done something that [[harm]]ed another: an instance of [[apologize|apologizing]] (saying that one is [[sorry]]).
#: ''What he said really hurt my feelings, but his '''apology''' sounded so sincere that I couldn't help but forgive him.''
#: ''The CEO made a public '''apology''' for the scandal, and promised full cooperation with the authorities.''
# A formal [[justification]], [[defence]].
#: ''The '''Apology''' of Socrates.''
# Anything provided as a [[substitute]]; a [[makeshift]].
#: ''a poor '''apology''' for a hotel room''
#* Charles Dickens
#*: He goes to work devising '''apologies''' for window curtains.

